   <h1>Boomerang</h1>
   <b>"S Hedberg" <shedberg51(-at-)hotmail.com></b><br/>
   <i>2002-02-19 21:07:36+00</i><br/>
   <br/>
   <pre>
I took a look at this site and have inquired as to availability and will 
post the list when I have something.  This technology looks effective but 
does have some "holes" in it... specifically if you live in an area that 
does not have very good cell coverage since it capitalizes on that 
technology already in place.

>From: "Léard, Michel" 
>To: 'George Lyle' , incynr8 
>CC: 'OldVolks General' , 'Thom Fitzpatrick'  
> , raymond.e.heath(-at-)boeing.com, swharris(-at-)earthlink.net, 
>vintagebus(-at-)type2.com
>Subject: RE: [VB] Stolen VW's
>Date: Tue, 19 Feb 2002 15:29:50 -0500
>
>
>hi
>
>quite a few car and trucks here have been succesfully found after a theft,
>yes they are stolen but they track it !!
>
>i think its kinda GPS system, its called Boomerang, they made the news a 
>few
>times because they found real quick the stolen vehicule, but i think its 
>new
>technology and not yet available everywhere...
>
>look them at:
>
>http://www.boomerangtracking.com/flash/fd_flash.html
>
>mike
>
>-----Message d'origine-----
>De : George Lyle [mailto:glyle(-at-)pon.type2.com]
>Envoyé : mardi 19 février 2002 14:15
>À : incynr8
>Cc : 'OldVolks General'; 'Thom Fitzpatrick'; raymond.e.heath(-at-)boeing.com;
>swharris(-at-)earthlink.net; vintagebus(-at-)type2.com
>Objet : RE: [VB] Stolen VW's
>
>
>
>
>On Tue, 19 Feb 2002, incynr8 wrote:
>
> > Does anyone thing lojack and/or alarms help? Are most of these being
> > towed away in the dark of night, or hot wired and driven away?
>
>Pro thieves use tow trucks.  Alarms will only help if you are within
>earshot, as people tend to ignore them due to excessive false alarms.
>Lojack is better, and they claim a 90% recovery rate.  The trick is to get
>to the vehicle before they disable the lojack or put the vehicle into a
>metal building.
>
> > The other thing,I was thinking, for longer term storage and shows was a
> > wheel boot.
>
>It would slow them down, but a pro will just winch it up onto his flatbed
>and drive away.  Better to chain it (with a hefty chain) to something
>substantial, or just to put it up on blocks and store the wheels
>elsewhere.
>
>Practically, in a parking lot, a club on the steering wheel with the
>wheels turned fully right or left will discourage a tow-truck equipped
>thief, as they cannot tow the car out of the space without it hitting
>adjacent cars.
>
>Of course, there is the classic Doberman on a long chain.
>
>George
>
>
